1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,566
Please give a round of applause
to our newlyweds!

2
00:00:06,866 --> 00:00:10,133
Mr. Pai, we are all here to tell you the truth.

3
00:00:10,166 --> 00:00:11,966
I’m useless to you now.

4
00:00:11,966 --> 00:00:13,400
Just get out of my life.

5
00:00:14,166 --> 00:00:17,866
I think you can trust him again when
he has no reason to scam you now.

6
00:00:18,333 --> 00:00:20,233
Let’s start over.

7
00:00:20,633 --> 00:00:21,800
Start over?

8
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:23,633
If you don’t love me, don’t say that.

9
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:25,366
I’m not giving up on you.

10
00:00:25,466 --> 00:00:26,933
Just watch out and try not to fall for me.

11
00:00:27,066 --> 00:00:27,400
Gecko!
Gecko!

12
00:00:29,033 --> 00:00:30,000
Where?

13
00:00:50,133 --> 00:00:50,800
What are you laughing at?

14
00:00:51,933 --> 00:00:52,666
Nothing.

15
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:55,733
Hey!

16
00:00:56,033 --> 00:00:56,866
What’s that for?

17
00:00:57,233 --> 00:00:57,866
Hey!

18
00:01:00,033 --> 00:01:00,800
Serves you right.

19
00:01:01,133 --> 00:01:02,533
You don’t take good care of your house

20
00:01:02,533 --> 00:01:03,633
that it nearly makes someone slip,

21
00:01:03,633 --> 00:01:04,400
and you laugh?

22
00:01:04,466 --> 00:01:06,733
Hey, have a little respect.

23
00:01:07,033 --> 00:01:08,266
I let you live here rent-free.

24
00:01:08,466 --> 00:01:09,933
You’re even wearing my clothes,
you know?

25
00:01:10,333 --> 00:01:11,600
I’m not staying for free.

26
00:01:11,866 --> 00:01:13,600
I’ll pay you back when I can.
Don’t you worry about that.

27
00:01:14,066 --> 00:01:15,733
You don’t need to.

28
00:01:16,333 --> 00:01:17,200
I’m more than happy to let you live here.

29
00:01:17,733 --> 00:01:19,033
Stay forever if you like.

30
00:01:19,233 --> 00:01:20,000
I don’t mind.

31
00:01:25,366 --> 00:01:25,633
Hey.

32
00:01:27,166 --> 00:01:27,766
What now?
I want a divorce.

33
00:01:30,333 --> 00:01:31,000
Today?

34
00:01:31,533 --> 00:01:32,400
I’m busy.
Tomorrow.

35
00:01:33,600 --> 00:01:34,600
Tomorrow?

36
00:01:35,766 --> 00:01:36,600
Let’s see…

37
00:01:38,133 --> 00:01:40,166
It says here there will be
heavy rainfall tomorrow.

38
00:01:40,433 --> 00:01:43,666
It is advised to stay inside
and just be nice and stay put.

39
00:01:43,933 --> 00:01:44,800
Are you messing with me?

40
00:01:45,133 --> 00:01:46,000
I’m not.

41
00:01:46,466 --> 00:01:47,600
Look at this.

42
00:01:47,966 --> 00:01:49,866
That’s what it says on the news.

43
00:01:49,866 --> 00:01:51,666
“Adorable people should
refrain from going outside.”

44
00:01:52,333 --> 00:01:53,800
“Handsome people shoul—” Ow!

45
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:00,633
Can you stop throwing
someone else’s stuff?

46
00:02:00,733 --> 00:02:01,800
Then be rational.

47
00:02:01,833 --> 00:02:03,033
How am I not being rational?

48
00:02:03,333 --> 00:02:04,933
I told you I’m not getting a divorce.

49
00:02:05,133 --> 00:02:06,066
You want a divorce?

50
00:02:06,433 --> 00:02:08,133
Sue me.

51
00:02:09,166 --> 00:02:10,566
And stop throwing my things.

52
00:02:13,266 --> 00:02:14,433
Everything’s ruined.

53
00:03:23,866 --> 00:03:28,400
Allow me to explain
what is going to happen.

54
00:03:28,933 --> 00:03:31,133
Upon signing this contract,

55
00:03:31,433 --> 00:03:35,166
you agree to a conciliation.

56
00:03:35,166 --> 00:03:37,633
You are no longer allowed
to make further claims whatsoever.

57
00:03:38,066 --> 00:03:41,866
You will not pursue any legal actions
or engage in public defamation.

58
00:03:42,533 --> 00:03:46,733
If you have any questions,
please consult the contract carefully.

59
00:03:46,733 --> 00:03:52,566
In return, Mr. Tim agrees
to compensate you for your troubles,

60
00:03:52,566 --> 00:03:55,466
which amounts to 69 million baht in total.

61
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:06,833
I’m kidding, Tim.

62
00:04:13,266 --> 00:04:18,333
You’re lucky Pai’s family insisted
they didn’t want your money.

63
00:04:18,333 --> 00:04:20,366
Otherwise, you wouldn’t be able
to afford to compensate these ladies.

64
00:04:20,366 --> 00:04:22,266
But since we’re on the topic,

65
00:04:22,266 --> 00:04:23,466
how the hell did you slip up so badly?

66
00:04:23,466 --> 00:04:29,166
You knew damn well love affairs are
always impossible to slither out of

67
00:04:29,166 --> 00:04:32,366
If I didn’t do that, how’d I find enough
money to pay Mr. Prasit back?

68
00:04:32,366 --> 00:04:34,533
Did you forget I have a
monthly debt commitment?

69
00:04:34,533 --> 00:04:36,933
Basically, you’re broke now, aren’t you?

70
00:04:40,033 --> 00:04:41,433
I’m not entirely broke, though.

71
00:04:42,266 --> 00:04:45,033
Besides the house and the car I won’t sell,

72
00:04:45,766 --> 00:04:47,933
I have 15 baht left in my bank account.

73
00:04:50,566 --> 00:04:51,200
That’s not a lot?

74
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:53,666
As you’ve all learned,

75
00:04:53,666 --> 00:04:58,566
we have been excluded from the Jeeramongkolthanun’s beneficiary list.

76
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:03,933
From now on, our lives depend on
what we have with us right this moment.

77
00:05:07,566 --> 00:05:08,466
Why do you look confused?

78
00:05:10,866 --> 00:05:14,800
Why do you talk like that?

79
00:05:15,066 --> 00:05:15,866
What do you mean?

80
00:05:16,166 --> 00:05:19,166
It sounds like we’re in a board meeting.

81
00:05:21,766 --> 00:05:22,633
It doesn’t.

82
00:05:23,333 --> 00:05:24,533
This is how I talk.

83
00:05:27,200 --> 00:05:27,833
You.

84
00:05:28,200 --> 00:05:29,833
You’re responsible for
today’s minutes of meeting.

85
00:05:31,033 --> 00:05:32,600
Y–Yes, Mr. Pai.

86
00:05:36,033 --> 00:05:36,666
North.

87
00:05:37,733 --> 00:05:39,400
What are minutes of meeting?

88
00:05:40,333 --> 00:05:41,600
Just write them on your phone.

89
00:05:42,233 --> 00:05:43,333
What am I supposed to write?

90
00:05:43,333 --> 00:05:44,400
Your feelings, duh.

91
00:05:44,400 --> 00:05:45,333
Just write it down.

92
00:05:45,333 --> 00:05:46,866
This is my wedding suit.

93
00:05:47,533 --> 00:05:48,733
I’m sure we can sell it.

94
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:51,566
I also have some cash on me…

95
00:06:00,733 --> 00:06:01,866
327 baht.

96
00:06:08,233 --> 00:06:09,533
How much do you guys have?

97
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:16,666
I already returned
the 250 million North gave me.

98
00:06:16,833 --> 00:06:17,433
North.

99
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:19,000
Where is that money right now?

100
00:06:20,633 --> 00:06:21,666
It’s in my bedroom.

101
00:06:23,833 --> 00:06:24,666
Typical North…

102
00:06:26,166 --> 00:06:27,133
You, too.

103
00:06:27,566 --> 00:06:29,166
How could you return
the money so willingly?

104
00:06:29,833 --> 00:06:30,466
What?

105
00:06:34,566 --> 00:06:35,133
MINUTES OF MEETING

106
00:06:35,133 --> 00:06:37,566
MINUTES OF MEETING
(Pai is poor.)

107
00:06:42,333 --> 00:06:44,633
What are you guys doing?

108
00:06:45,866 --> 00:06:46,833
Hey, Tim.

109
00:06:47,166 --> 00:06:49,166
We’re trying to sort out
how much money we have.

110
00:06:49,166 --> 00:06:53,266
Pai wants to know how long
what we have will last us.

111
00:06:54,066 --> 00:06:54,800
I see.

112
00:07:06,133 --> 00:07:06,766
Whoa.

113
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:09,766
Do you carry the rings around
with you all the time?

114
00:07:09,766 --> 00:07:10,200
Yeah.

115
00:07:10,833 --> 00:07:13,533
Just in case I need to propose again.

116
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:15,766
Thanks.

117
00:07:17,833 --> 00:07:19,200
But I don’t take anything from a thief.

118
00:07:46,533 --> 00:07:48,066
And don’t you wear that ring again.

119
00:07:49,133 --> 00:07:49,933
North.

120
00:07:50,800 --> 00:07:53,166
Don’t you have any cash or asset
that don’t belong to the family?

121
00:07:53,366 --> 00:07:55,466
Grandpa used to give you money
on the side, didn’t he?

122
00:07:56,833 --> 00:07:57,566
Right.

123
00:08:04,600 --> 00:08:05,233
Hey.

124
00:08:05,633 --> 00:08:06,400
How are you, dude?

125
00:08:08,233 --> 00:08:09,066
You alright?

126
00:08:10,233 --> 00:08:11,866
I…

127
00:08:13,833 --> 00:08:14,766
No.

128
00:08:15,333 --> 00:08:15,800
North.

129
00:08:17,133 --> 00:08:19,266
I told you to close this place down.

130
00:08:19,733 --> 00:08:21,066
You’ve been lying to me all this time?

131
00:08:24,766 --> 00:08:26,000
Pai, before you say anyth—

132
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:26,966
Thank you, North.

133
00:08:27,266 --> 00:08:28,033
We’re saved!

134
00:08:39,133 --> 00:08:40,800
CLOSED!
FOR OUR FIRST EVER MEETING

135
00:08:54,066 --> 00:08:58,066
I have to admit that you and Pure
make really good pastries.

136
00:09:01,433 --> 00:09:01,966
But…

137
00:09:03,366 --> 00:09:04,433
But what now?

138
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:08,600
But if you continue your business like this,

139
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,033
it won’t turn a profit even in 10 years.

140
00:09:13,433 --> 00:09:16,066
This place has made us money before,
you know?

141
00:09:16,066 --> 00:09:18,600
One day doesn’t count.

142
00:09:20,133 --> 00:09:21,400
Don’t make such a fuss, Pai.

143
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:25,066
If you want it to make profits,
I’ll pay for that myself.

144
00:09:25,066 --> 00:09:27,766
How would it be called profits
if you did that?

145
00:09:28,733 --> 00:09:31,266
One more thing, we are not
borrowing money from anyone.

146
00:09:31,666 --> 00:09:35,566
North, you’re not allowed
to be in debt or cause trouble now.

147
00:09:36,433 --> 00:09:40,533
The only way we’ll survive this
is to make this place turn a profit.

148
00:09:41,433 --> 00:09:44,833
I want you to hire me as your employee.

149
00:09:45,033 --> 00:09:46,966
I ask for only 500 baht a day.

150
00:09:46,966 --> 00:09:51,066
And I guarantee a 3000% growth
for your business.

151
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:55,366
Alright.

152
00:09:55,366 --> 00:09:56,666
You’re hired.

153
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:03,000
We’ll start with cost-cutting by removing
any menu items that don’t sell.

154
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:03,600
Hold on.
No.

155
00:10:04,066 --> 00:10:06,166
That’s a no-no.

156
00:10:06,166 --> 00:10:07,033
I said no.

157
00:10:11,033 --> 00:10:13,833
I want you to bake based on
the ingredients in the fridge.

158
00:10:13,833 --> 00:10:15,266
You’re not allowed to order more supplies

159
00:10:15,266 --> 00:10:16,766
unless you run out
of the pre-existing ingredients.

160
00:10:16,766 --> 00:10:18,366
Is that a dare?

161
00:10:21,233 --> 00:10:22,233
Not unless you can’t do it.

162
00:10:29,366 --> 00:10:30,633
Do your best, bud.

163
00:10:35,166 --> 00:10:35,766
Excuse me.

164
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:38,666
Yes, Mr. Pai?

165
00:10:39,166 --> 00:10:42,233
I’m sorry but your service
is no longer required here.

166
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:47,033
A resignation letter?
Yes.

167
00:10:48,533 --> 00:10:52,000
MATCHA YUZU CROISSANT
AND BASIL LEMON TART

168
00:10:57,533 --> 00:11:00,533
Oh, you’re back to work now.

169
00:11:01,233 --> 00:11:01,766
I am.

170
00:11:03,666 --> 00:11:04,833
Hello.

171
00:11:04,833 --> 00:11:06,133
What can I get you today?

172
00:11:07,066 --> 00:11:07,466
Of course.

173
00:11:07,466 --> 00:11:09,033
Donut?

174
00:11:09,333 --> 00:11:11,000
Here is your orange americano.

175
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:11,933
Thanks.

176
00:11:13,633 --> 00:11:15,000
Pai, careful. It’s hot.

177
00:11:15,066 --> 00:11:16,266
I told you to bake croissants.

178
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:18,966
North, careful!
Just take this.

179
00:11:20,133 --> 00:11:21,466
Pai, let me know when you’re home.

180
00:11:24,266 --> 00:11:24,866
Here.

181
00:11:31,833 --> 00:11:32,333
Oh.

182
00:11:33,266 --> 00:11:34,666
Come and have dinner, you guys.

183
00:11:35,033 --> 00:11:35,833
It’s still hot.

184
00:11:36,400 --> 00:11:36,766
Come on.

185
00:11:46,433 --> 00:11:48,033
Stop looking for excuses.

186
00:11:48,366 --> 00:11:49,733
I won’t charge you for this.

187
00:11:51,966 --> 00:11:53,166
That’s a bitter melon, North.

188
00:11:53,733 --> 00:11:55,733
Well, I used to study abroad, you know?

189
00:11:59,733 --> 00:12:00,600
Thank you for your service.

190
00:12:10,400 --> 00:12:11,233
Over there?
That table, U.

191
00:12:12,433 --> 00:12:13,266
Just go.

192
00:12:13,666 --> 00:12:14,000
North.
Americano?

193
00:12:14,633 --> 00:12:15,366
Pai, one americano, please.

194
00:12:19,800 --> 00:12:20,333
I’ll put them here, Pai.
Thanks.

195
00:12:23,766 --> 00:12:24,166
Here’s the food.
What would you like?

196
00:12:26,866 --> 00:12:29,833
I won’t let you change my recipe
just like this.

197
00:12:30,066 --> 00:12:31,666
Just get off my back.

198
00:12:32,633 --> 00:12:34,533
I’m not trying to pick a fight, Pure.

199
00:12:34,533 --> 00:12:37,766
I just don’t think we need to import
the chocolate straight from Belgium.

200
00:12:37,766 --> 00:12:39,666
But it’s my recipe!

201
00:12:40,566 --> 00:12:42,266
Tarte au chocolat noir blanc.

202
00:12:42,266 --> 00:12:44,000
It needs ‘chocolat noir blanc.’

203
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,533
It wouldn’t be “tarte au chocolat
noir blanc” otherwise!

204
00:12:46,533 --> 00:12:47,466
It wouldn’t!

205
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:50,533
I won’t let you—

206
00:12:54,133 --> 00:12:54,766
What are you doing here?

207
00:12:55,233 --> 00:12:57,933
I just want to try North’s pastry.

208
00:12:58,000 --> 00:12:59,333
We’re out.

209
00:13:01,433 --> 00:13:02,200
You are?

210
00:13:02,766 --> 00:13:04,566
You must do really well.
You need any new hires?

211
00:13:04,566 --> 00:13:05,433
No.

212
00:13:05,433 --> 00:13:06,666
We’re managing it fine on our own.

213
00:13:07,133 --> 00:13:08,600
You sure about that?

214
00:13:09,800 --> 00:13:12,333
Iced chocolate coming up, ma’am.

215
00:13:12,633 --> 00:13:15,200
Irasshaimase!

216
00:13:17,266 --> 00:13:18,000
Oh.

217
00:13:18,966 --> 00:13:20,033
Tim.

218
00:13:20,033 --> 00:13:21,433
Hey, Tim.

219
00:13:21,433 --> 00:13:22,033
When did you get here?
Are you hungry?

220
00:13:22,600 --> 00:13:24,033
I’ll find something for you to eat.

221
00:13:25,566 --> 00:13:26,400
I’m fine.

222
00:13:26,400 --> 00:13:28,333
What are you doing here anyway?

223
00:13:28,433 --> 00:13:30,933
I was wondering if you need someone
to work here part-time.

224
00:13:30,933 --> 00:13:31,600
You’re hired!

225
00:13:31,966 --> 00:13:32,666
North, no.

226
00:13:33,566 --> 00:13:34,866
Why not?

227
00:13:35,266 --> 00:13:36,800
We’re at our limits!

228
00:13:37,066 --> 00:13:41,633
Having more help during this time is good!

229
00:13:42,266 --> 00:13:43,966
I don’t mind working as an unpaid intern.

230
00:13:46,533 --> 00:13:52,733
I just want something to do
before I start my new job.

231
00:13:53,466 --> 00:13:55,000
Aren’t you curious about my new job?

232
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:55,933
No one is.

233
00:13:58,200 --> 00:13:59,733
I’ll start tomorrow.

234
00:13:59,733 --> 00:14:00,400
Wow.

235
00:14:10,566 --> 00:14:11,733
I have to go.

236
00:14:11,733 --> 00:14:13,800
I have to talk to a potential buyer.

237
00:14:14,566 --> 00:14:16,533
They’re interested in
distributing our pastries.

238
00:14:17,166 --> 00:14:17,933
Can I give you a ride?

239
00:14:18,233 --> 00:14:19,033
Leave me alone.

240
00:14:28,266 --> 00:14:31,466
I don’t think it’s a good idea
to be strolling around here.

241
00:14:31,466 --> 00:14:32,466
Hello. We have so many
new flavors of macarons.
- Hello. We have so many
new flavors of macarons.
- Why?

242
00:14:33,166 --> 00:14:34,266
Hello. We have so many
new flavors of macarons.

243
00:14:34,266 --> 00:14:37,066
Well, now that I’m broke,

244
00:14:37,066 --> 00:14:39,633
I feel like I’m just here to watch people eat.

245
00:14:39,633 --> 00:14:41,633
But I can’t buy anything if I want to.

246
00:14:47,233 --> 00:14:47,800
What’s wrong, North?

247
00:14:51,466 --> 00:14:52,633
I don’t want to torture myself.

248
00:14:55,533 --> 00:14:56,000
Oh?

249
00:14:56,800 --> 00:14:57,733
Why’d you let go of my hand?
Hello.

250
00:14:58,200 --> 00:15:00,033
Hello, our special customer.

251
00:15:00,033 --> 00:15:02,433
We have a TikTok dance challenge promotion, sir.

252
00:15:03,533 --> 00:15:04,466
TikTok…

253
00:15:05,933 --> 00:15:07,166
Dance challenge?

254
00:15:17,466 --> 00:15:18,233
Hold on.

255
00:15:18,600 --> 00:15:19,133
Alright?

256
00:15:19,633 --> 00:15:21,133
One, two, three.

257
00:15:29,333 --> 00:15:30,233
U, go for it.

258
00:15:30,533 --> 00:15:31,233
U!

259
00:15:37,266 --> 00:15:38,000
Alright.

260
00:15:51,333 --> 00:15:53,866
So this is what it tastes like to be human.

261
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:56,966
That was so good.

262
00:16:01,166 --> 00:16:05,000
Oh, I forgot to share it with you.

263
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:05,733
I’m sorry.

264
00:16:13,933 --> 00:16:14,533
I got it.

265
00:16:15,833 --> 00:16:16,533
It’s good.

266
00:16:17,366 --> 00:16:17,966
Sweet.

267
00:16:28,966 --> 00:16:29,833
Are you embarrassed?

268
00:16:38,166 --> 00:16:39,000
Does it look like I am?

269
00:16:41,966 --> 00:16:42,466
No.

270
00:16:43,533 --> 00:16:44,366
But I am.

271
00:16:55,233 --> 00:16:57,333
Good morning, brothers.

272
00:16:58,066 --> 00:16:59,366
Good morning, Mr. Pai.

273
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:00,866
Sit down.

274
00:17:01,433 --> 00:17:02,266
We’ll have breakfast.

275
00:17:03,933 --> 00:17:07,000
What is Tim doing
having breakfast here alone?

276
00:17:07,533 --> 00:17:08,166
I’m fine.

277
00:17:09,066 --> 00:17:10,366
I am fine, sir.

278
00:17:11,166 --> 00:17:12,966
Mr. Tim here wants some privacy.

279
00:17:13,333 --> 00:17:14,066
Totally, North.

280
00:17:14,400 --> 00:17:15,933
I love private breakfasts.

281
00:17:16,033 --> 00:17:18,633
But seeing as Pai must be lonely,
I came and sat with him.

282
00:17:19,233 --> 00:17:20,200
Go on and have breakfast, you guys.
Morning, by the way.

283
00:17:21,366 --> 00:17:21,800
Morning.
You okay?

284
00:17:22,866 --> 00:17:23,533
Yeah.
Right.

285
00:17:28,966 --> 00:17:29,966
Oh, right.

286
00:17:30,200 --> 00:17:34,866
How was it talking to the…
potassium slider… slim?

287
00:17:34,966 --> 00:17:36,333
Potential buyer.

288
00:17:37,466 --> 00:17:39,166
It’s someone who’s interested
in buying our products.

289
00:17:39,966 --> 00:17:41,600
I think it’s interesting.

290
00:17:42,466 --> 00:17:44,966
They want to put our pastries up
in convenience stores.

291
00:17:45,266 --> 00:17:46,733
If it really does happen,

292
00:17:47,366 --> 00:17:49,333
our daily income will likely
exceed our expectations.

293
00:17:49,333 --> 00:17:51,733
Does that mean we’ll be rich again?

294
00:17:51,933 --> 00:17:52,400
Yes.

295
00:17:53,733 --> 00:17:55,066
But I don’t think we’re ready for that.

296
00:17:57,066 --> 00:17:57,933
Why not?

297
00:17:57,933 --> 00:17:59,266
If we agree to this deal,

298
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:03,333
we have to increase our product output,
and thus, also our manpower

299
00:18:03,833 --> 00:18:05,600
just to meet their demand.

300
00:18:05,866 --> 00:18:08,333
That will require at least a million that
we don’t have right now.

301
00:18:12,133 --> 00:18:14,866
What if we asked Pure for the loan?

302
00:18:15,833 --> 00:18:18,200
I understand you don’t want
to borrow anyone’s money.

303
00:18:18,933 --> 00:18:21,600
But if it’s the money to expand
our business,

304
00:18:21,933 --> 00:18:23,166
I think it makes sense.

305
00:18:23,266 --> 00:18:24,833
I contacted Pure.

306
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:29,266
He said a million would be quite troublesome for him as well.

307
00:18:30,533 --> 00:18:31,933
But he always travels.

308
00:18:32,166 --> 00:18:36,000
I believe he’s been pressured by
the family to not help us out.

309
00:18:36,466 --> 00:18:38,300
The mess we made might not
become a national scandal,

310
00:18:39,400 --> 00:18:41,200
I’ll try to look more into it.

311
00:18:44,266 --> 00:18:46,166
I’ll try to look more into it.

312
00:18:46,166 --> 00:18:47,566
Do your best, guys!

313
00:18:47,566 --> 00:18:48,366
We got this.

314
00:18:48,600 --> 00:18:49,900
You put us in this situation so shut up.

315
00:18:49,900 --> 00:18:50,533
Yessir!

316
00:18:51,533 --> 00:18:52,833
Shall we have breakfast?

317
00:18:53,033 --> 00:18:53,700
What did I just say?

318
00:18:54,500 --> 00:18:55,066
Sorry.

319
00:18:59,700 --> 00:19:02,266
Thank you for arranging this.

320
00:19:02,733 --> 00:19:04,400
Of course.

321
00:19:05,033 --> 00:19:06,466
Just talk to her nicely.

322
00:19:06,633 --> 00:19:07,233
Right.

323
00:19:08,300 --> 00:19:09,533
There she is.

324
00:19:13,966 --> 00:19:14,700
Oom.

325
00:19:15,400 --> 00:19:17,566
You told me you wanted
to talk to me about work.

326
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:19,800
I have to go.

327
00:19:19,800 --> 00:19:21,200
I just remember I left the iron running.

328
00:19:21,566 --> 00:19:22,633
It must be burning at this point.

329
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:29,733
Are you scamming patients now?

330
00:19:29,900 --> 00:19:30,800
Just leave me be.

331
00:19:31,433 --> 00:19:32,900
Say what you want to say.

332
00:19:34,433 --> 00:19:35,000
Mom.

333
00:19:35,966 --> 00:19:38,966
You remember the one million
you stole from me?

334
00:19:42,100 --> 00:19:43,066
What money?

335
00:19:43,233 --> 00:19:44,400
I don’t remember that.

336
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:45,433
Don’t lie.

337
00:19:46,333 --> 00:19:49,500
We both know it was you who took it.

338
00:19:50,866 --> 00:19:51,966
Just give it back to me.

339
00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:55,866
The person that money belongs
to really needs it right now.

340
00:19:56,100 --> 00:19:57,400
Is that so?

341
00:20:00,133 --> 00:20:02,266
Do you mean the grandson of a tycoon

342
00:20:05,333 --> 00:20:08,766
If he’s in trouble with money,
that means he’s useless to you now.

343
00:20:09,366 --> 00:20:10,666
Why don’t you just leave him?

344
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:11,966
I love him.

345
00:20:12,466 --> 00:20:14,333
I don’t want to cause trouble
for someone I love.

346
00:20:14,600 --> 00:20:16,500
I thought I taught you better than this, U.

347
00:20:17,800 --> 00:20:21,200
Love is useless to the likes of us.

348
00:20:22,166 --> 00:20:23,700
Unless it’s our weapon.

349
00:20:25,500 --> 00:20:27,366
And since it’s a weapon,

350
00:20:28,966 --> 00:20:31,200
you shouldn’t use it to hurt yourself.

351
00:20:32,566 --> 00:20:34,466
Love makes you weak.

352
00:20:36,066 --> 00:20:40,833
And weak people are taken advantage of.

353
00:20:44,166 --> 00:20:44,800
Mom.

354
00:20:46,300 --> 00:20:47,800
I never asked anything of you.

355
00:20:48,966 --> 00:20:51,100
But I’m asking you this.

356
00:20:52,533 --> 00:20:53,700
Give me back that money.

357
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:58,766
If you want it, you will have to
call the cops on me.

358
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:08,733
Thank you.

359
00:21:30,266 --> 00:21:34,000
He is so easy on the eye, isn’t he?

360
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:38,600
Wanna join my “my boyfriend
used to be a conman” club?

361
00:21:39,633 --> 00:21:40,766
You’re talking nonsense.

362
00:21:43,433 --> 00:21:44,466
Where’s U today?

363
00:21:45,166 --> 00:21:46,133
He has some errand to run.

364
00:21:46,266 --> 00:21:47,566
I think he’ll be back by evening.

365
00:21:50,666 --> 00:21:51,000
North.

366
00:21:52,333 --> 00:21:53,000
Yes?

367
00:21:53,533 --> 00:21:55,166
Why are you still dating U?

368
00:21:55,800 --> 00:21:57,266
He scammed you

369
00:21:59,166 --> 00:22:01,366
Yes, he scammed me.

370
00:22:01,866 --> 00:22:03,066
But he doesn't do that anymore.

371
00:22:03,333 --> 00:22:05,600
How do you know he’s not
fooling you right now?

372
00:22:07,666 --> 00:22:10,500
I mean, if he was using me,
he might have run away already.

373
00:22:11,466 --> 00:22:13,100
But I’m no use to him now.

374
00:22:13,900 --> 00:22:18,100
So if he chooses to stay,
that must mean that he loves me.

375
00:22:30,333 --> 00:22:31,233
Aren’t you mad at him?

376
00:22:32,766 --> 00:22:35,600
Well, I was.

377
00:22:35,666 --> 00:22:37,866
But I don’t think you can
stay mad at someone forever.

378
00:22:49,566 --> 00:22:50,433
Hey, Tim.

379
00:22:50,933 --> 00:22:51,600
What are you talking about?

380
00:22:52,466 --> 00:22:53,033
None of your business.

381
00:22:58,466 --> 00:23:01,100
I’ll go put this in the kitchen.

382
00:23:03,300 --> 00:23:04,400
I don’t wanna be caught in the crossfire.

383
00:23:11,166 --> 00:23:11,766
Tired?

384
00:23:13,700 --> 00:23:14,733
Do you want a massage?

385
00:23:17,366 --> 00:23:17,966
Come here.

386
00:23:23,100 --> 00:23:24,533
I’m good at this, you know?

387
00:23:29,600 --> 00:23:30,133
Is it here?

388
00:23:53,033 --> 00:23:55,300
Your iced yuzu, sir.

389
00:24:00,200 --> 00:24:01,633
How did you know I’d be here?

390
00:24:02,466 --> 00:24:05,733
A friend of mine said they saw you
at this cafe.

391
00:24:07,333 --> 00:24:09,700
How are you doing?

392
00:24:11,133 --> 00:24:12,000
I’m getting by.

393
00:24:12,266 --> 00:24:13,166
Why didn’t you tell me?

394
00:24:13,466 --> 00:24:14,666
You know I’m always here for you.

395
00:24:15,433 --> 00:24:18,000
You know I don’t want to
owe anyone anything.

396
00:24:21,833 --> 00:24:25,866
Why are you still with…

397
00:24:30,033 --> 00:24:30,733
Forget that.

398
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:35,566
Why did you come to see me?

399
00:24:40,700 --> 00:24:41,033
Pai.

400
00:24:42,200 --> 00:24:43,266
Can we talk outside?

401
00:24:43,333 --> 00:24:44,766
I don’t feel comfortable talking in front of...

402
00:24:48,033 --> 00:24:48,833
It’s hot outside, though.

403
00:25:04,233 --> 00:25:06,233
LAND TITLE DEED

404
00:25:07,266 --> 00:25:10,133
It’s the title deed of the land of
our gated community project.

405
00:25:11,533 --> 00:25:12,533
I’m returning it to you.

406
00:25:13,466 --> 00:25:14,766
I just thought you might need it.

407
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:19,066
Thank you, Kuea.

408
00:25:19,700 --> 00:25:20,966
This totally saves me.

409
00:25:26,200 --> 00:25:26,966
He’s lost it.

410
00:25:27,666 --> 00:25:30,333
Look at him pacing the floor.

411
00:25:30,700 --> 00:25:31,866
Poor man.

412
00:25:39,100 --> 00:25:39,833
I have to go.

413
00:25:40,366 --> 00:25:41,400
Thank you

414
00:25:43,166 --> 00:25:43,900
Bye, you guys.

415
00:25:44,666 --> 00:25:45,533
- Bye.
- Bye.

416
00:26:04,633 --> 00:26:05,000
Hey.

417
00:26:08,966 --> 00:26:09,366
Tim.

418
00:26:12,866 --> 00:26:13,266
Me?

419
00:26:13,900 --> 00:26:14,266
Yeah.

420
00:26:15,766 --> 00:26:16,400
What’s up?

421
00:26:20,800 --> 00:26:22,000
Would you like to have dinner tonight?

422
00:26:27,533 --> 00:26:28,033
…Yes.

423
00:26:29,833 --> 00:26:30,433
You promise?

424
00:26:32,833 --> 00:26:33,666
I’ll call and reserve a table.

425
00:26:38,966 --> 00:26:39,833
Hello.

426
00:26:41,966 --> 00:26:43,800
Have a little patience, Pai.

427
00:26:44,166 --> 00:26:45,633
Tim seems down bad lately.

428
00:26:55,100 --> 00:26:55,500
North.

429
00:26:56,400 --> 00:26:57,233
I’ll leave early.

430
00:26:57,866 --> 00:26:59,566
Make sure you hurry home
after you lock up.

431
00:26:59,966 --> 00:27:00,833
I’ll see you at home

432
00:27:01,333 --> 00:27:02,366
Okay.

433
00:27:02,833 --> 00:27:03,500
Just go.

434
00:27:03,633 --> 00:27:04,733
I’ll handle the rest.

435
00:27:15,066 --> 00:27:15,566
Pure, let me help.

436
00:27:16,433 --> 00:27:17,100
Thank you, man.

437
00:27:25,900 --> 00:27:29,333
I’m sorry, but we’re closed.

438
00:27:45,266 --> 00:27:47,300
You don’t have the kind of money
that can reserve this whole place

439
00:27:51,400 --> 00:27:53,166
Just forget about that kind of thing.

440
00:28:00,733 --> 00:28:02,233
I took out a loan on my car.

441
00:28:02,733 --> 00:28:04,133
You shouldn’t live beyond your means

442
00:28:05,300 --> 00:28:07,700
Don’t you realize we’re legally one person.

443
00:28:08,300 --> 00:28:09,900
I don’t want to have to be liable
to any debts you incur.

444
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:12,100
I just…

445
00:28:13,700 --> 00:28:16,133
I want to give you what you were used to.

446
00:28:28,300 --> 00:28:31,766
Why… did you suddenly want
to have dinner with me?

447
00:28:35,366 --> 00:28:36,200
I want a divorce.

448
00:28:38,900 --> 00:28:39,700
Don’t change the subject

449
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:43,833
I want to have a serious
conversation about this.

450
00:28:49,133 --> 00:28:50,933
Did Kuea put you up to this?

451
00:28:54,333 --> 00:28:54,800
Yes.

452
00:28:56,733 --> 00:28:58,733
He suggested I get a divorce from you.

453
00:28:59,600 --> 00:29:00,833
I’m worried about you, Pai.

454
00:29:01,033 --> 00:29:02,433
As long as you’re still married to Tim,

455
00:29:03,100 --> 00:29:07,033
this land is a marital asset
and belongs to both you and Tim.

456
00:29:07,166 --> 00:29:12,666
I suggest you get a proper divorce
before managing this property.

457
00:29:15,266 --> 00:29:17,000
But even if Kuea didn’t say anything,

458
00:29:17,833 --> 00:29:19,466
I still want a divorce.

459
00:29:20,966 --> 00:29:21,800
Think about it.

460
00:29:22,166 --> 00:29:23,633
I don’t know you at all.

461
00:29:24,400 --> 00:29:26,000
I married someone I barely know.

462
00:29:28,166 --> 00:29:29,066
You understand, don’t you?

463
00:29:33,600 --> 00:29:34,533
Please.

464
00:29:36,200 --> 00:29:37,533
Give me a divorce.

465
00:29:40,700 --> 00:29:42,066
Let’s not take this matter to court.

466
00:29:49,500 --> 00:29:50,800
If this is about money,

467
00:29:55,333 --> 00:29:56,700
I’ll divorce you.

468
00:29:58,866 --> 00:29:59,233
But…

469
00:30:08,533 --> 00:30:11,100
But can we just have
this one last proper dinner?

470
00:30:32,100 --> 00:30:33,233
Oh, you’re back.

471
00:30:34,700 --> 00:30:35,166
Yeah.

472
00:30:36,266 --> 00:30:39,400
I went to the bakery, but it was closed.

473
00:30:40,400 --> 00:30:41,966
So I guessed you must have come home

474
00:30:43,500 --> 00:30:44,333
But…

475
00:30:45,300 --> 00:30:46,433
Where are Pai and Tim?

476
00:30:46,666 --> 00:30:48,900
They’re at dinner.

477
00:30:49,033 --> 00:30:49,366
What?

478
00:30:50,033 --> 00:30:50,500
Right?

479
00:30:50,866 --> 00:30:52,033
I was just as confused.

480
00:30:53,533 --> 00:30:55,933
I didn’t see my boyfriend all day today.

481
00:30:55,933 --> 00:30:56,633
I miss you.

482
00:30:56,900 --> 00:30:59,033
Come here and let me get my fill of you.

483
00:31:03,733 --> 00:31:04,266
Did that hurt?
Sorry.

484
00:31:05,533 --> 00:31:06,233
It didn’t hurt.

485
00:31:10,566 --> 00:31:11,800
Your eyes are swollen.

486
00:31:12,166 --> 00:31:13,033
What’s happened?

487
00:31:14,200 --> 00:31:15,600
Have you been crying?

488
00:31:17,500 --> 00:31:18,033
Uh…

489
00:31:21,500 --> 00:31:24,133
I… went to see Nart today.

490
00:31:25,333 --> 00:31:28,333
I wanted her to return the
one million she stole.

491
00:31:28,700 --> 00:31:29,466
I guessed it.

492
00:31:31,366 --> 00:31:32,400
What do you mean you guessed it?

493
00:31:35,033 --> 00:31:40,966
So… Nart came to see me
at the bakery today.

494
00:31:40,966 --> 00:31:41,200
What?

495
00:31:43,033 --> 00:31:44,366
I don’t know what she wanted.

496
00:31:44,433 --> 00:31:47,433
She was speaking in circles like
she just wanted to get close to me.

497
00:31:47,700 --> 00:31:49,633
But since I knew
what kind of person she is,

498
00:31:50,133 --> 00:31:51,400
I just don’t trust her anymore.

499
00:31:51,633 --> 00:31:53,833
Did she get anything out of you, North?

500
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:54,833
Of course not.

501
00:31:55,766 --> 00:31:57,266
I don’t have anything
for her to take, you know?

502
00:31:59,300 --> 00:31:59,900
Okay.

503
00:32:00,100 --> 00:32:01,100
But let’s talk about you.

504
00:32:02,300 --> 00:32:03,300
Why were you crying?

505
00:32:06,833 --> 00:32:09,333
It’s just the same old thing
that ends the same old way.

506
00:32:10,966 --> 00:32:12,466
I love my mother.

507
00:32:12,966 --> 00:32:15,900
I just don’t think
she can turn herself around.

508
00:32:20,766 --> 00:32:24,633
I think all you can do is let her go

509
00:32:25,533 --> 00:32:27,833
and be with people
who love and care for you,

510
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:30,466
and hope she doesn’t hurt you again.

511
00:32:36,900 --> 00:32:38,866
I care about you, you know?

512
00:32:39,133 --> 00:32:40,000
I really do.

513
00:32:50,900 --> 00:32:51,233
Thank you.

514
00:33:02,333 --> 00:33:03,833
Was I an easy target?

515
00:33:05,100 --> 00:33:06,033
Not really.

516
00:33:07,933 --> 00:33:09,566
You’re kind of stubborn.

517
00:33:10,200 --> 00:33:11,400
You like challenges

518
00:33:12,500 --> 00:33:14,200
even when you keep complaining
that it’s exhausting.

519
00:33:14,966 --> 00:33:17,933
So I put you in some
challenging situations at first.

520
00:33:18,833 --> 00:33:22,600
Once you accepted the challenge,
you began to have fun.

521
00:33:23,633 --> 00:33:26,966
Once you had fun,
you let your guard down.

522
00:33:27,866 --> 00:33:32,066
After that, I just let
my gentlemanly side take the lead.

523
00:33:34,533 --> 00:33:36,566
You stripped me bare, didn’t you?

524
00:33:41,500 --> 00:33:42,266
Do you have any more questions?

525
00:33:48,866 --> 00:33:50,066
Is Tim really your name?

526
00:33:52,766 --> 00:33:53,600
It is!

527
00:33:57,600 --> 00:33:59,233
You didn’t even think about using an alias?

528
00:33:59,466 --> 00:34:03,666
It just kinda slipped out
the first time I met you.

529
00:34:06,133 --> 00:34:09,833
That moment felt really special.

530
00:34:12,433 --> 00:34:14,433
It didn’t feel like I was scamming anyone.

531
00:34:15,300 --> 00:34:15,533
Oh.

532
00:34:17,066 --> 00:34:17,733
I’m Tim.

533
00:34:18,333 --> 00:34:18,966
I’m Pai.

534
00:34:19,900 --> 00:34:22,300
So I let my actual name slip out.

535
00:34:23,133 --> 00:34:24,433
It was like…

536
00:34:25,533 --> 00:34:28,800
I was actually flirting
with someone I really wanted.

537
00:34:32,666 --> 00:34:33,600
Was it hard playing Tim?

538
00:34:34,966 --> 00:34:35,733
What do you mean?

539
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:38,400
Well, you know…

540
00:34:39,533 --> 00:34:41,700
Being someone who was

541
00:34:42,733 --> 00:34:44,266
created exactly just for me.

542
00:34:44,966 --> 00:34:45,733
It was hard.

543
00:34:47,466 --> 00:34:50,666
Like I said, it wasn’t me at all.

544
00:34:51,533 --> 00:34:56,700
To tell you the truth, I don’t think
someone like him exists.

545
00:34:58,066 --> 00:34:59,400
He’s like…

546
00:35:01,466 --> 00:35:02,366
A unicorn.

547
00:35:02,700 --> 00:35:03,700
Too good to be true.

548
00:35:07,166 --> 00:35:08,300
It’s too bad.

549
00:35:09,533 --> 00:35:11,266
I’d love to meet him just one more time.

550
00:35:13,600 --> 00:35:14,333
That Tim?

551
00:35:16,066 --> 00:35:16,466
Yeah.

552
00:35:17,800 --> 00:35:18,333
Alright.

553
00:35:24,700 --> 00:35:25,400
Hey, baby.

554
00:35:33,366 --> 00:35:34,266
What’s the matter?

555
00:35:36,733 --> 00:35:37,866
Don’t laugh.

556
00:35:38,466 --> 00:35:39,666
You’re making me break character.

557
00:35:39,966 --> 00:35:41,233
Now I have to start again.

558
00:35:41,633 --> 00:35:42,733
Alright, alright.

559
00:35:43,033 --> 00:35:43,800
I won’t laugh.

560
00:35:44,633 --> 00:35:45,166
Come on.

561
00:35:49,500 --> 00:35:50,266
Hey, baby.

562
00:35:51,766 --> 00:35:52,466
What’s the matter?

563
00:36:06,133 --> 00:36:06,966
I have something to tell you.

564
00:36:08,533 --> 00:36:09,266
Close your eyes.

565
00:37:22,633 --> 00:37:26,866
I can give you an extra discount
if you pay cash upfront.

566
00:37:28,466 --> 00:37:29,866
What do you think?

567
00:37:30,333 --> 00:37:33,100
You can tell we use all the best materials.

568
00:37:33,100 --> 00:37:35,466
The construction is stable
and durable so—

569
00:37:35,466 --> 00:37:36,133
Hello, Mom.

570
00:37:38,766 --> 00:37:42,500
Why don’t we move inside?

571
00:37:42,500 --> 00:37:43,433
Please.

572
00:37:43,666 --> 00:37:45,533
I’ll be right with you.

573
00:37:45,533 --> 00:37:46,633
Please.

574
00:37:49,266 --> 00:37:50,333
What is it now?

575
00:37:50,400 --> 00:37:51,633
I told you I won’t give it back.

576
00:37:52,200 --> 00:37:54,100
If you want it so bad, call the cops.

577
00:37:54,200 --> 00:37:55,033
I did.

578
00:37:58,566 --> 00:38:00,033
It’s thanks to North that

579
00:38:00,633 --> 00:38:04,500
now I understand I should be
with someone who loves me,

580
00:38:04,766 --> 00:38:07,933
not someone who only hurts me,

581
00:38:08,833 --> 00:38:10,700
and take advantage of North.

582
00:38:11,633 --> 00:38:12,700
I can’t let you do that, Mom.

583
00:38:16,066 --> 00:38:16,966
I call your bluff.

584
00:38:18,466 --> 00:38:20,100
I know you don’t have the guts to do that.

585
00:38:20,700 --> 00:38:22,133
I raised you myself.

586
00:38:26,200 --> 00:38:26,766
I…

587
00:38:27,900 --> 00:38:29,166
I didn’t do it myself.

588
00:38:30,800 --> 00:38:31,433
He did.

589
00:38:38,433 --> 00:38:39,400
His name is Prem.

590
00:38:40,433 --> 00:38:44,600
He is a criminal defense attorney
behind our country’s top con artists.

591
00:38:46,800 --> 00:38:48,400
I already asked him to handle everything.

592
00:38:49,733 --> 00:38:51,200
If you ever want to turn over a new leaf,

593
00:38:52,400 --> 00:38:56,500
I’ll be here, waiting to be your family again.

594
00:39:06,866 --> 00:39:07,466
Sir. Ma’am.

595
00:39:11,300 --> 00:39:12,066
Go home.

596
00:39:14,066 --> 00:39:16,500
This woman is a con artist.

597
00:39:18,800 --> 00:39:21,066
I know because
she has conned me before.

598
00:39:58,400 --> 00:39:59,100
You’re up.
Yeah.

599
00:40:01,033 --> 00:40:02,266
I had something to do this morning.

600
00:40:02,433 --> 00:40:03,400
How was it?

601
00:40:03,800 --> 00:40:04,400
You okay?

602
00:40:04,700 --> 00:40:06,966
With you here, of course, I am.

603
00:40:10,900 --> 00:40:11,500
Thank you.

604
00:40:11,966 --> 00:40:12,933
For what?

605
00:40:17,966 --> 00:40:18,866
I don’t know.

606
00:40:19,900 --> 00:40:20,933
I just want to thank you.

607
00:40:21,266 --> 00:40:22,266
You’re being weird.

608
00:40:29,700 --> 00:40:32,033
I don’t want to get up.

609
00:40:34,333 --> 00:40:36,200
But I need to do my laundry,

610
00:40:36,766 --> 00:40:40,900
and Pai wants me to go to
the district office with him.

611
00:40:42,333 --> 00:40:43,466
What is he doing at the district office?

612
00:40:44,700 --> 00:40:45,966
I don’t know.

613
00:40:50,366 --> 00:40:53,533
Well, why don’t I do the laundry?

614
00:40:54,166 --> 00:40:55,166
Go back to bed.

615
00:40:56,633 --> 00:40:57,733
You’re the best.

616
00:40:59,133 --> 00:40:59,733
Good night.

617
00:41:25,933 --> 00:41:26,533
Oh, hey.

618
00:41:27,566 --> 00:41:27,966
Can I put my laundry in your load?

619
00:41:31,400 --> 00:41:31,733
Hey.

620
00:41:36,366 --> 00:41:36,866
Hey!

621
00:41:39,533 --> 00:41:40,700
You need to use the washing machine?

622
00:41:40,966 --> 00:41:41,300
Yeah.

623
00:41:42,633 --> 00:41:43,166
Where’s your mind at?

624
00:41:44,466 --> 00:41:45,633
You look like a kicked puppy.

625
00:41:46,333 --> 00:41:47,900
You went to dinner
with Mr. Pai last night, right?

626
00:41:48,100 --> 00:41:48,833
Didn’t you guys make up?

627
00:41:49,900 --> 00:41:51,166
Pai said he wants a divorce.

628
00:41:52,533 --> 00:41:53,600
I already agreed to it.

629
00:41:58,766 --> 00:42:00,700
That’s why you’re going to
the district office.

630
00:42:03,566 --> 00:42:03,900
Come on.

631
00:42:04,366 --> 00:42:05,166
It’s alright.

632
00:42:05,433 --> 00:42:06,066
Take it easy.

633
00:42:06,366 --> 00:42:08,966
I got divorced before
getting back together as well.

634
00:42:09,100 --> 00:42:10,300
There’s still hope.

635
00:42:10,933 --> 00:42:11,466
Don’t be discouraged.

636
00:42:11,966 --> 00:42:12,166
Alright?

637
00:42:14,200 --> 00:42:14,733
Smile.

638
00:42:15,233 --> 00:42:15,666
I’ll go.

639
00:42:16,433 --> 00:42:17,033
Thanks for this.

640
00:42:56,200 --> 00:42:56,800
Where is Tim?
Why isn’t he here?

641
00:42:58,533 --> 00:43:00,833
I just met him out back doing laundry.

642
00:43:02,500 --> 00:43:02,933
Hey!

643
00:43:06,200 --> 00:43:07,433
Is he trying to get out of this?

644
00:43:18,733 --> 00:43:19,066
Hey!

645
00:43:21,966 --> 00:43:22,366
Hey.
Are you hurt?

646
00:43:23,166 --> 00:43:23,733
What’s happened?
Hey!

647
00:43:24,366 --> 00:43:25,433
North! U!

648
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:26,500
North!
Pai?
Yes?

649
00:43:28,133 --> 00:43:28,466
Oh!

650
00:43:29,600 --> 00:43:30,333
- Tim!
- Tim!

651
00:43:31,500 --> 00:43:31,800
Tim.

652
00:43:40,033 --> 00:43:41,400
Mr. Thanin is safe now.

653
00:43:41,466 --> 00:43:42,333
Can I see him?

654
00:43:42,500 --> 00:43:42,800
Yes.

655
00:43:45,433 --> 00:43:46,700
Thank you, Doctor.

656
00:43:58,366 --> 00:43:59,500
This is not a ruse, is it?

657
00:44:01,966 --> 00:44:03,366
Why were you so careless?

658
00:44:03,600 --> 00:44:05,666
I told you to scrub the algae off
that part of the floor.

659
00:44:09,433 --> 00:44:10,100
I’m sorry.

660
00:44:11,166 --> 00:44:12,400
You’re always like this, baby.

661
00:44:12,733 --> 00:44:13,466
I don’t like it.

662
00:44:14,833 --> 00:44:15,733
What did you just call me?

663
00:44:23,033 --> 00:44:24,000
Don’t make fun of me.

664
00:44:24,500 --> 00:44:25,600
I’m still shaken.

665
00:44:26,200 --> 00:44:27,100
Sorry.

666
00:44:28,666 --> 00:44:32,266
From the look of it, I don’t think
they’re getting divorced.

667
00:45:04,800 --> 00:45:09,300
The worst part for me is that
I can’t be there to support you.

668
00:45:10,900 --> 00:45:13,033
Just come to one date with me.

669
00:45:13,200 --> 00:45:14,200
Please!

670
00:45:14,400 --> 00:45:15,400
Stop making a ruckus.

671
00:45:15,700 --> 00:45:18,933
If you’re still in love with him
and believe in him,

672
00:45:19,200 --> 00:45:20,633
why would you need someone new?

673
00:45:21,200 --> 00:45:24,566
You ever met someone you know
was the one for you

674
00:45:24,566 --> 00:45:26,266
that you can’t love someone else?

